==English==

===Noun===
{{en-noun|tricks of the trade}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} A [[shortcut]] or other quick, or very effective way of doing things, that [[professional]] workers learn from [[experience]].
#* {{quote-text|lang=en|year=1858|author=Thomas Carlyle|title=Critical and Miscellaneous Essays|page=130|passage=For the most part, he has some knack, or '''trick of the trade''', which by close inspection can be delected, and so the heart of his mystery be seen into.}}
#* '''1861''', ''Blackwood's Edinburgh Magazine'', page 520,
#*: There is no '''trick of the trade''' which he does not know, no artifice which he does not which he does not habitually practise.
#* {{quote-text|lang=en|year=2006|author=Ed van Hinte|title=Under Cover: Evolution of Upholstered Furniture|page=60|passage=Most customers won't notice this '''trick of the trade''', since the part is not sat upon.}}

====Usage notes====
* This term most often appears as {{m|en||the tricks of the trade}}; indeed, for many speakers this is the only form. Such speakers typically use the locution {{m|en||one of the tricks of the trade}}. Other speakers use uncountable {{m|en||the trick of the trade}} to refer collectively to all such shortcuts and more efficient techniques.

